author: Mimi Morley
time required: 30 minutes
---

Peel the @Kiwi{1}, then cut into 1cm chunks. Halve the @Red Chilli{1} lengthways, deseed, then finely chop.

Zest and halve the @Lime{1}.

Pop the kiwi and chilli into a #bowl{} and squeeze in the lime juice and @Olive Oil{for the salsa}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, mix together then set aside.

Pour the @Water{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Jasmine Rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pot{} from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Halve the @Sugar Snap Peas{80%g} lengthways down the middle. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @?oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the sugar snap peas and stir-fry until tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pop the sugar snaps into a bowl and cover with #foil{} to keep warm.

Return the frying pan to a medium-high heat and add a drizzle of @?oil{}. Drain the @King Prawns{150%g} and pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Once hot, add the prawns to the pan. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and cook for ~{4-5%minutes}. The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Remove the pan from the heat and pour in the @Teriyaki Sauce{50%ml}.

Gently toss to combine and coat the prawns in the sauce.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

Share the rice between your #bowls{}, then serve the teriyaki prawns, kiwi salsa (including the juices) and sugar snaps in separate sections on top.

Enjoy!